Sanders is the overwhelming favourite here. His polling lead has held at 15-20% throughout the campaign and new polls today by Change Research and PBP gave him a lead of 19 points. A lead of 19 points gives him around a 90% chance of success. This is significantly more than the crowd who imply he only has a 73% chance of winning.

Buttigieg's campaign strategy of focusing one state at a time seems to be faltering, going from first to second to third and towards another low finish in South Carolina. This definitely takes the wind out of his sails and showcases his campaign's inability to multitask on several states at a time, this will only be exacerbated on Super Tuesday. Therefore, while polls tend to under predict his support, it remain infeasible for him to ultimately more than double his support in California while also campaigning in multiple other states.

The 2/20 Monmouth poll (A+ rating on FiveThirtyEight) on the California democratic primary shows Sanders at 24%, Biden at 17%, Bloomberg at 13%, Warren at 10%, Pete at 9%, and Klobuchar at 4%. Sanders should still be favored to win, but I believe the 2/19 democratic debate diminished Bloomberg's chances but increased Warren's chances. Biden has been trending downwards, and Pete has leveled off.
Bernie is leading in early polling in California by a substantial margin, and didn't lose by much in 2016.

Out of all of the primary races, this will probably be one of the tightest. Sanders will edge all of the candidates because of his stance on many social economic issues that directly impact many Californians. California has the city with the highest cost of living (San Francisco), and affordable living and access to jobs that pay a living wage will be a deciding factor in this election.
Bernie is on the rise. People don't like Bloomberg more stuff coming out by the hour. Pete is still looking good. He was excellent o. The CNN Town hall

Sanders polling very strongly, with the website 538 giving him a 68% chance at the moment. I have adjusted this upwards, demographics in this State favour him and i thing momentum from performance of states leading up to Super Tuesday increases the probability he wins the majority. Bloomberg's marketing blitz has propelled him into contention and he has a similar chance to Biden.

Bernie has been ahead in California for almost a month now, even before he started winning in Primary States and the latest poll after NH and Iowa indicate a surge/continuance of support around the crucial 25% mark and over, therefore Bernie has polling has been polling at winning number for a while. This support will only grow has Bernie is likely going to win Nevada and come in 2nd or 3rd in South Carolina, above other "popular" prospects like Buttigieg, Klobuchar and Warren. One should also not forget that Bernie has the highest level of support among Hispanic voters, which is a huge voting demographic in California and will likely propel him towards a victory there.

The vote will still be split between more liberal and more moderate candidates by the time of the California primary. Given that CA is a relatively liberal state, I give the combination of Bernie Sanders and Elizabeth Warren a slight edge. Mike Bloomberg's strength would be in providing a more electable alternative to both the liberals and to more centrist candidates like Klobuchar, Biden and Buttigieg, but I don't believe that the panic among the centrists will have set in yet, especially among the more liberal CA voters.
